      {
        "id": 2460894,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2018-08-06T22:27:20.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>You\u2019re absolutely right that this is a fantastic site.</p>\n<p>Potinet-Ampeau have designated it for a long time.</p>\n<p>The Clos des Rougets, the walled enclave within Rougeots that abuts the Tesson of Roulot and Pierre Morey, was vinified a few times by Verget and Deux Montilles. My understanding is that it goes into the Bouchard Meursault villages now. A pity.</p>\n<p>I believe the etymology derives from the site\u2019s red soils, and that it was once planted with red grapes. I had always assumed that the difference between Rougeots and Chevali\u00e8res was due to exposition, as Chevali\u00e8res turns to the north subtly and is more exposed to cooling winds, but when I discussed this with Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Coche, he argued that this was not the case, and that the differences are owing principally to geology. Sure enough, the photo below shows the rocks you find in Rougeots (below) and those you find in Chevali\u00e8res (above)\u2014they are separated by a narrow path.<br>\n<br>\n<br>\n<img src=\"https://i.imgur.com/Kze5hns.jpg?3\" alt=\"\"></p>",
        "post_number": 2,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 4,
        "updated_at": "2022-06-03T05:31:30.401Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
